{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17630203","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17630203"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T17:15:32+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T17:15:32+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17309"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"17309","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/17309"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0,0,0.04,0.61,0.36]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9999"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"69825"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"9999","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/9999"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17309"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"55281"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4930"},{"type":"tags","id":"4931"},{"type":"tags","id":"4941"},{"type":"tags","id":"7237"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"23417"},{"type":"contributions","id":"23421"},{"type":"contributions","id":"23431"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"69825","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/69825"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EThere are a number of nerves responsible for the cutaneous sensation in the lower limb.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following nerves is responsible for providing sensation to the web space between the first and second toes?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Femoral","Obturator","Sciatic","Superficial fibular","Deep fibular"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe web space between the first and second toes is innervated by the \u003Cstrong\u003Edeep fibular nerve\u003C/strong\u003E. This nerve is a branch of the common fibular nerve, which itself is a branch of the sciatic nerve. The deep fibular nerve provides sensory innervation to this specific area of the foot.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Esuperficial fibular nerve\u003C/strong\u003E provides sensation to the majority of the dorsum of the foot, but not the web space between the first and second toes.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Etibial nerve\u003C/strong\u003E provides sensation to the sole of the foot, not the dorsum or the web space between the first and second toes.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Efemoral nerve\u003C/strong\u003E primarily innervates the anterior thigh and does not provide sensation to the foot.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Eobturator nerve\u003C/strong\u003E innervates the medial thigh and does not provide sensation to the foot.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The deep fibular nerve provides sensation to the web space between the first and second toes.","The superficial fibular nerve provides sensation to the dorsum of the foot, except for the web space between the first and second toes.","The tibial nerve provides sensation to the sole of the foot."],"references":["Sakellariou VI, Badilas NK, Mazis GA, Stavropoulos NA, Kotoulas HK, Kyriakopoulos S, Tagkalegkas I, Sofianos IP. Brachial plexus injuries in adults: evaluation and diagnostic approach. ISRN Orthop. 2014 Feb 9;2014:726103. doi: 10.1155/2014/726103. PMID: 24967130; PMCID: PMC4045362","Singh, V. (2024). Textbook of Clinical Neuroanatomy-E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences","Michael-Titus, A. T., \u0026 Shortland, P. (2022). The Nervous System, E-Book: The Nervous System, E-Book. Elsevier Health Science","Merryman J, Varacallo M. Klumpke Palsy. 202